  "text": "The JavaScript parsing and bytecode compilation chain in SpiderMonkey follows this architecture:\n\n## Entry Point: BytecodeCompiler\nThe compilation process begins in `js/src/frontend/BytecodeCompiler.h` with the `CompileGlobalScript()` function (line 532 in BytecodeCompiler.cpp), which serves as the high-level driver for the entire compilation pipeline. This function orchestrates the parsing and bytecode generation steps according to the architectural documentation in the header file (lines 28-103 of BytecodeCompiler.h).\n\n## Parser: Generating AST\nThe Parser class is defined in `js/src/frontend/Parser.h` (line 1679) and is heavily templatized along the ParseHandler axis (FullParseHandler for full parsing, SyntaxParseHandler for syntax-only parsing) and along the Unit axis (character type). The parser converts JavaScript source text into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) composed of ParseNode objects.\n\n## AST Node Types: ParseNode Hierarchy\nThe AST nodes are defined in `js/src/frontend/ParseNode.h` and include:\n\n- **ParseNode** (line 712): Base class for all AST nodes, which is type-identified by ParseNodeKind enum\n- **UnaryNode** (line 952): Represents unary operations with a single child node (e.g., `!x`, `-y`)\n- **BinaryNode** (line 1017): Represents binary operations with left and right child nodes (e.g., `x + y`, `x && y`)\n- **TernaryNode** (line 1115): Represents ternary conditional operations with three child nodes (e.g., `x ? y : z`)\n- **ListNode** (line 1184): Represents lists of nodes for statements and expressions\n- **NameNode**, **NumericLiteral**, **StringExpr**, **FunctionNode**, **AssignmentNode**, **ForNode**, and many others\n\nEach node type implements a `test()` static method for type checking and maintains position information (`pn_pos`) for source mapping.\n\n## Bytecode Emitter: Generating Bytecode\nThe BytecodeEmitter is defined in `js/src/frontend/BytecodeEmitter.h` (line 210) and emits bytecode from the AST. Key aspects:\n\n- Receives the AST from the Parser\n- Separates bytecode into prologue and main sections (lines 96-98 of BytecodeEmitter.h)\n- Uses helper classes like ClassEmitter, PropertyEmitter, CallOrNewEmitter for specific constructs\n- Emits bytecode instructions using various emit methods\n- The `emitScript()` function (BytecodeEmitter.cpp, line 2354) is the entry point for emitting script bytecode\n\n## Bytecode Output: JSScript\nThe final bytecode is stored in a JSScript object, defined in `js/src/vm/JSScript.h` (line 1787). Key methods:\n\n- `JSScript::Create()` (line 1800): Creates a JSScript instance\n- `JSScript::fullyInitFromStencil()` (line 1818): Initializes JSScript from the compilation stencil\n- `JSScript::fromStencil()` (line 1826): Allocates and initializes a JSScript with bytecode\n- `code()` (line 1844): Returns pointer to the bytecode array (`jsbytecode*`)\n- `immutableScriptData()` (line 1839): Returns the immutable script data containing the bytecode\n\nThe bytecode can be navigated using BytecodeLocation (`js/src/vm/BytecodeLocation.h`) which provides utilities for working with bytecode positions within a JSScript.\n\n## Data Flow Summary\nJavaScript source → BytecodeCompiler → Parser → ParseNode AST → BytecodeEmitter → Bytecode instructions → JSScript with embedded bytecode"
}

